What is Git?

Git is a version control system used to:

Track changes in source code

Save code history

Work on projects locally (offline)

Git runs on your local machine

Common Git Commands
git init        # initialize repository
git status      # check file status
git add .       # add files to staging
git commit -m "message"   # save changes

What is GitHub?

GitHub is an online platform used to:

Store Git repositories in the cloud

Share code with others

Collaborate with teams

Backup projects

 GitHub works online

Key Difference Between Git and GitHub
Git	GitHub
Tool / Software	Website / Platform
Works locally	Works online
Tracks code changes	Hosts Git repositories
No internet required	Internet required
Created by Linus Torvalds	Owned by Microsoft
Real-Life Example 

Git â†’ Like saving multiple versions of a file on your laptop

GitHub â†’ Like uploading that file to Google Drive and sharing it

Basic Git + GitHub Workflow

Create a project locally

git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"


Push project to GitHub

git remote add origin <repo-url>
git push -u origin main

When to Use What?

Use Git to:

Track changes

Manage versions

Work offline

Use GitHub to:

Share projects

Collaborate with others

Store code online

Short Summary 

Git = Version control tool
GitHub = Online platform for Git repositories
